\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{Fig_221_2013_7anew.jpg}
\caption{Figure for reflection A}
\end{figure}

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  For any non-trivial reflection, the eigenvalues are always \emph{1}
  and \emph{-1}.
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  For the eigenvalue 1, we can pick any vector on the line itself. Such
  a vector will not be moved by the linear transformation. So, for us,
  we pick $\left[ \begin{array}{c}4 \\ 3 \end{array} \right]$ as an
  eigenvector to the eigenvalue 1. Note that \emph{(x,y) = (4,3)} is a
  point on the line \emph{3x=4y} since \emph{3(4)=4(3)}.
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  The eigenvalue of \emph{-1} comes from picking a vector in the line
  that is perpendicular (i.e. orthogonal) to the line $4y = 3x$. Any
  such vector will simply change its sign, thus will correspond to the
  eigenvalue \emph{-1}. We choose
  $\left[ \begin{array}{c} -3 \\ 4 \end{array} \right]$ as an
  eigenvector to the eigenvalue -1.
\end{itemize}
